Based on the above results, the mechanism of T-GQDs toward OFL/LEV detections can be explained as follows (
                           Fig. S17
                        ). First, when excited by an external light source, the core of T-GQDs generates electron excitons that transfer to the edge and recombine at the edge functional group energy level, resulting in the edge state emission at 414 nm. After the addition of OFL/LEV, the electrostatic bonds are formed between OFL/LEV molecules and T-GQDs, which provide channels for the electron transfer from T-GQDs to OFL/LEV by the intermolecular ET effect. Therefore, it is the intermolecular ET effect that leads to the reduction of electrons trapped in the edge states of T-GQDs, inducing the fluorescence quenching at 414 nm. Instead, electrons are transferred to OFL/LEV and recombined at lower-energy surface fluorophores, promoting the fluorescence-enhanced emission at 498 nm.
